# ventd — grant the logged-in seat user access to Corsair USB devices.
#
# The daemon runs unprivileged (User=ventd, Group=ventd; see
# deploy/ventd.service). It accesses Corsair Commander Core, Commander Core XT,
# and Commander Pro AIO controllers via /dev/hidraw* devices. This rule tags
# the Corsair USB parent device (VID 0x1b1c) with "uaccess" — systemd-logind
# grants the active seat user access to the matching hidraw child node
# without requiring ventd to run as root, use a sidecar, or hold CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE.
#
# Installed to:
#   /etc/udev/rules.d/90-ventd-liquid.rules
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Design: subsystem = usb, not hidraw.
#
# This rule matches the USB parent device (SUBSYSTEM=="usb") rather than the
# hidraw child (SUBSYSTEM=="hidraw"). The hidraw node inherits the uaccess tag
# from its parent and does not need a separate rule. Matching the parent is
# safer: the USB device is always present when the device is plugged in, and
# the ATTRS{idVendor} filter is exact. A hidraw-level rule would require
# matching the HID descriptor or relying on kernel to populate the hidraw
# driver, adding latency and complexity.
#
# Why uaccess, not group grant.
#
# ventd exposes a web UI; the logged-in seat user should control cooling,
# not an arbitrary "ventd" group. The "uaccess" tag (defined in systemd
# logind) is the modern Discretionary Access Control primitive on systemd
# systems. It assigns read/write access to the device node only for the
# current seat's active user, with automatic cleanup on logout. An
# alternative (ventd group + daemon socket) would add a sidecar and violate
# the "single binary, no sidecar" architecture promise. A root-privileged
# daemon is strictly worse — ventd is sandboxed and capability-bounded in
# deploy/ventd.service, and CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE is never restored.
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Reload after editing:
#   sudo udevadm control --reload
#   sudo udevadm trigger --subsystem-match=usb
#
# The installer (scripts/install.sh and scripts/postinstall.sh) runs
# both commands automatically after placing this file, so no operator
# action is required on a clean install.

SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTRS{idVendor}=="1b1c", TAG+="uaccess"
